InfoFi: Emerging Speculation Markets

Patryk Krasnicki
Alice Hou
Armita

May 22, 2025 â‹…  12 min read

Key Insights

  • Information Finance (InfoFi) is an emerging category of applications that introduces tradable markets that enable financial speculation on exotic, non-price data points.
  • These applications arenâ€™t just a new avenue for financial speculation. InfoFi markets support information discovery based on the financial activity occurring within them.
  • Polymarket has become an InfoFi mainstay, serving as a lens into the real-time probabilities of real-life events. The concept of Multiverse Finance could be Polymarket's next evolution.
  • InfoFi is expanding beyond prediction markets, as applications like Noise, Ethos, and Narrative support information discovery via tradable markets for mindshare, reputation, and quantitative metrics.
  • InfoFi can be intentional, where the desired information to be elicited can be determined preemptively before a new market is created. Emergent speculation markets may lead to unexpected information discoveries.

Primer

Information Finance (InfoFi) is an emerging category of applications in the crypto economy. The most common tradable markets, in crypto or otherwise, are price-related. One can go long or short cryptocurrencies, equities, and commodities, or trade options pegged to price outcomes. InfoFi, on the other hand, creates exotic, non-price tradable markets that users can speculate on. Assuming reasonable market efficiencies, these markets can convey new, valuable information. Hence the nameâ€”InfoFi.

The application that popularized InfoFi in 2024 was Polymarket, a prediction market where users can speculate on real-life event outcomes. Activity on the application reached a frenzied peak during the 2024 U.S. presidential election as the protocol saw $512.3 million in open interest (USD).

After facilitating billions of dollars in monthly trading volume, Polymarket was touted as one of the most accurate predictors of the election's outcome. Polymarket is now seen as a lens into the true probabilities of real-life events like a US-China trade deal, Suez Canal traffic, or leading large language models, all enabled by InfoFi.

Today, InfoFi is expanding beyond prediction markets. Protocols like Noise, Ethos, and Narrative aim to create tradable markets for mindshare, reputation, and quantitative metrics. Meanwhile, the concept of Multiverse Finance could be the next evolution for Polymarket. InfoFi creates new avenues for speculation while enabling the discovery of new information whose accuracy is â€œbackedâ€ by the underlying financial activity.

Noise

Noise is a protocol that features tradable markets for crypto project mindshare, allowing users to speculate on attention trends, not tokens. These markets are perpetual, can be leveraged up to 5x, and are priced in real-time based on independent third-party data streams. Kaito serves as Noiseâ€™s first oracle, powering mindshare markets by indexing sources across social media, forums, news, and podcasts.

Noiseâ€™s tradable markets expand outside of token price action, which is often unpredictable and influenced by a variety of complex factors like token unlocks, insider selling, and market making. Noise allows users to speculate on how projects will fare in terms of attention, irrespective of token price action. Previously, if one was bullish on a projectâ€™s product(s), core team, or sector, they could take a position related to the tokenâ€™s price. With Noise, one can capitalize on these predictions while stripping away the idiosyncratic risks present for the token. Not to mention, Noise opens a new avenue to speculate on tokenless projectsâ€™ attention, like PumpFun and OpenSea.

Founded by Luca, Sator, and Gabo, Noise went live on MegaETH testnet on March 31, 2025, in an invite-only beta. As a part of MegaETHâ€™s cohort of projects dubbed the â€œMegaMafia,â€ Noise receives high-touch support from the MegaETH core team and ecosystem, and has received a positive reception. Per Lucas, Noise has seen a 30-day user retention rate of 64.2%, with an average session duration of 12.5 minutes. Assuming this level of engagement remains consistent, and significant trading volume follows upon mainnet launch, Noise will enable market participants to assess market sentiment about project attention relative to current mindshare.

Despite no point program or airdrop incentives having been announced, Noise has seen sustained usage post-launch. Since launch, Noise has expanded its tradable markets to 13 projects, including the likes of Monad, Infinex, Abstract, and Sophon. With the team actively hiring engineers, new markets and products could be coming soon. Still, various issues loom that will need to be addressed leading up to a mainnet launch, including liquidity concerns, oracle diversity, closed-source oracle models, and susceptibility to data manipulation.

Long term, the core team has stated that Noiseâ€™s endgame is to â€œreinvent what it means to discover and distribute culture.â€ Compounded with hints about ideas of supporting mindshare markets for individuals, narratives, or brands, Noiseâ€™s long-term ambitions extend outside of crypto. Imagine trading artist or song popularity during the Kendrick Lamar vs. Drake feud using Chartmetric as an oracle, or trading American football player grades using Pro Football Focus as an oracle. These ideas are in the cards for Noise. The result could be a novel application that pierces through the crypto bubble into mainstream consumer appeal in todayâ€™s attention-driven world.

Ethos

Ethos is an onchain credibility protocol designed to make trust legible and enforceable in crypto. The project introduces a decentralized system where reputation is shaped through socially driven mechanisms such as reviewing, which provides lightweight, non-anonymous feedback. This is reinforced by economically backed actions like vouching, where users can stake ETH on others, and slashing, a dispute resolution process that allows users to challenge false or unethical behavior. Each user has a credibility score, similar to a credit score but native to Web3. Credibility scores are generated from onchain behavior and social feedback, and are surfaced through a public Ethos Profile. Ethos Markets complements the core protocol by enabling users to speculate on the credibility of identities, ranging from individuals to DAOs, via reputation-linked markets tied to EVM addresses.

Ethos was founded by the pseudonymous Serpin Taxt (@0x5f_eth), a former hedge fund day trader. Notably, Ethos raised a $1.75 million pre-seed round backed by 59 individual angel investors without participation from VCs or a named lead. Since launching on Base mainnet on January 22, 2025, the protocol has seen steady adoption, with over 7,500 profiles created and ongoing vouching activity across the network.

Participation in Ethos is gated by invitation, and each new connection triggers a 90-day bonding period. During this time, the inviter shares 20% of the inviteeâ€™s credibility score, whether it rises or falls. This mechanism disincentivizes careless invites, as bringing in a bad actor who loses credibility can negatively impact the inviterâ€™s own score.

The slashing mechanism on Ethos has already driven heated debates and shown its potential in real-world situations. Slashing allows any user to accuse another of unethical behavior, triggering a 24-hour freeze on the accused's stake and a validator vote, with outcomes that can financially or reputationally penalize the accused and their vouchers.

Earlier this month, an Ethos user named Chad.farm initiated a high-profile slash against CZ, the former CEO of Binance, accusing him of being dishonest and untrustworthy. The accusation centered on CZâ€™s comments implying that Dingaling, an influential crypto figure with prior ties to Binance, had fabricated his past role, despite evidence suggesting otherwise. The slash proposal narrowly failed by a single vote, but marked one of the first widely shared uses of slashing on Ethos and highlighted the protocolâ€™s potential to hold prominent figures accountable through onchain credibility markets.

Ethos presents a compelling experiment in crypto reputation systems, tackling a foundational problem, trust, in a distinctly crypto-native way. Over time, if adoption continues, Ethos credibility scores may serve as an early warning system by detecting bad actors or questionable projects via rapid shifts in social sentiment and vouch behavior. The scoring system has already begun to demonstrate utility beyond theory. For example, the platform's credibility scores for Movement began to decline as early as April 13, nearly three weeks before Coinbaseâ€™s delisting of Movement and co-founder Rushi Mancheâ€™s departure from the company. Finally, Movementâ€™s score saw a sharp drop on May 4 as the news became more widely known and confirmed.

On the other hand, Ethos raises concerns reminiscent of sci-fi critiques, such as the Nosedive episode from Black Mirror, where individuals feel pressured to conform in order to maintain high social ratings.

In a similar way, Ethos users may begin to tailor their behavior not out of genuine integrity, but to optimize for a better credibility score. This dynamic risks creating a homogenized environment where authentic expression is sacrificed for reputational gain.

The introduction of Ethos Market adds another layer of complexity. Though positioned as a complementary product for reputation speculation, it effectively turns trust into a tradable asset. This financialization of credibility opens the door to manipulation, including coordinated attacks, reputational shorting, and other actions motivated by profit rather than ethical concerns.

Note: The section on Ethos was written by Alice Hou (@FBitach).

Multiverse Finance

Multiverse Finance is a conceptual idea created by Dave White of Paradigm. Instead of simply betting on outcomes like in a prediction market, Multiverse lets you step into full financial ecosystems built around â€œwhat ifâ€ scenarios. Each of these ecosystems, called verses, represents a possible version of the future. Verses operate as self-contained worlds where users can build, invest, and take positions that only increase in value if that version of the future actually plays out.

Each verse in Multiverse Finance is part of a structured hierarchy. The current world, or â€œtodayâ€™s universe,â€ is the broadest parent verse; it contains all possible outcomes. Specific futures, like â€œTaylor Swift releases her next album in 2026â€ or â€œTaylor Swift does not release her next album in 2026,â€ form a partition of this parent verse, meaning theyâ€™re mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive. Ownership of assets can move between these layers. If you hold a token in a parent verse, you can push down your ownership to its child verses in the partition, splitting one token into conditional claims across possible outcomes. Later, if you hold tokens in each child verse, and the outcome is resolved, you can pull up ownership into the resolved parent verse. Multiverse uses a data structure called the multiverse map to track these relationships, ensuring that ownership remains consistent across outcomes.

Ideally, within each verse, users can do almost everything they would in a regular DeFi protocol: borrow, lend, swap, provide liquidity, and earn yield. For example, in a verse where Taylor Swift does not release her next album in 2026, you might use noAlbumUSD to borrow noAlbumETH, provide liquidity on noAlbumSwap, and stake in noAlbumFarm. Because both your collateral and your loan are tied to the same outcome, they rise or fall together, eliminating bad debt risk.

Multiverse Finance addresses a core limitation of traditional prediction markets like Polymarket: conditional tokens (e.g., noAlbumUSD) are typically isolated and unusable across other applications, forcing users to passively hold positions until resolution. This leads to capital inefficiency and makes these markets less integrated with the broader financial stack. Multiverse reimagines this model by introducing self-contained financial "verses" where every asset is scoped to a specific outcome, enabling fully functional DeFi ecosystems such as borrowing, lending, and trading within each possible future. By allowing conditional assets to flow across composable applications and using data structures like the multiverse map to represent belief and hedge uncertainty, Multiverse expands the design space for event-driven financial systems. In doing so, it builds on the foundation laid by Polymarket and other InfoFi pioneers, suggesting a broader trajectory for markets that do not just reveal prices but organize economic activity around the discovery and resolution of real-world information.

Note: The section on Multiverse Finance was written by Alice Hou (@FBitach).

Narrative

Narrative is an in-development protocol on Monad (a high-performance, Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM)-compatible Layer 1 network) being built by former Messari intern Patrick Kim. Initially conceived as a way to speculate on dominant crypto narratives: memes, theses, and storylines; Narrative has since pivoted toward a more data-driven model. Rather than capturing collective belief or sentiment directly, the protocol now prices derivatives based on real-time blockchain and exchange data.

A market tied to the â€œAI x Cryptoâ€ theme might be priced using the total open interest in related assets. For example, if open interest on Hyperliquid reaches $4.1 billion, the derivative could be priced at $4.10. This structure allows users to take directional exposure to crypto-native activity metrics, rather than speculating purely on token price or narrative sentiment.

While platforms like Noise aim to reflect market attention and Ethos captures trust, Narrative focuses on the underlying quantitative indicators that often shape these signals. Within the InfoFi context, it introduces a more structured and data-oriented layer of abstraction.

Although Narrative doesnâ€™t surface collective conviction in the same way as Polymarket or Noise, market participants are still expressing beliefs about future activity trends, whether open interest will rise, onchain activity will increase, or a sector will gain traction. As a result, while it may not fully align with belief-driven InfoFi protocols, it sits adjacent to the category: not a market of sentiment, but a system for speculating on the performance metrics that reflect emerging narratives.

Note: The section on Narrative was written by Armita Jalooli (@AJalooli).

Conclusion

Information Finance (InfoFi) is an emerging category of applications that introduce tradable markets that allow users to speculate on exotic, non-price signals. InfoFi is expanding beyond prediction markets, as protocols like Noise, Ethos, and Narrative create tradable markets for mindshare, reputation, and quantitative metrics, while concepts like Multiverse Finance iterate on prediction markets that have already achieved product-market fit.

InfoFi isnâ€™t just a new avenue for financial speculation. These markets are supporting information discovery based on the financial activity occurring within them. Tomorrowâ€™s InfoFi protocols wonâ€™t be from happenstance. InfoFi can be intentional, where the desired information to be elicited can be determined preemptively before a new market is created. Todayâ€™s pioneering InfoFi protocols are leading the way, but as the category matures, expect emergent speculation markets to lead to unexpected information discoveries.
